      "QuestionText": "What is best-case time complexity of Bubble sort to sort an array of 'n' elements?",
      "Options": [
        {
          "OptionId": "A",
          "OptionText": "O(n^2)"
        },
        {
          "OptionId": "B",
          "OptionText": "O(n log n)"
        },
        {
          "OptionId": "C",
          "OptionText": "O(1)"
        },
        {
          "OptionId": "D",
          "OptionText": "O(n)"
        }
      ],
      "Status": 1,
      "Remarks": null,
      "SubjectId": 72,
      "UniqueNodeId": 4278,
      "QuestionTypeId": 0,
      "QuestionId": 88812,
      "Explanation": "<span id=\"explanation88812\">The best-case time complexity of Bubble Sort occurs when the array is already sorted. In this scenario, Bubble Sort will only need to make one pass through the array to verify that it is sorted. During this single pass, no swaps are made, and the algorithm will recognize that the array is sorted and terminate early. </span>",
      "Answer": "D",
      "Marks": 0
